import VersoManual

open Verso.Genre Manual

#doc (Manual) "Voices from the Field" =>

%%%
shortTitle := "Voices"
%%%

Quantum mechanics was built by people who wrote and argued vividly about what
they were doing, and their sharper lines have become part of the subject's
folklore. This chapter collects some of them, one per contributor, as a way of
meeting the cast before meeting the mathematics.

The book's citation discipline (see the core invariant) applies here without
exception: every quotation below is traced to a *primary* published source, its
author's own book, paper, lecture, or a dated letter. Many of the most-repeated
"quantum quotes" are recollections, compressions, or outright misattributions;
those are not printed as authored quotations. A closing section names the ones
we deliberately left out and why. Where a source is a multi-author paper, the
co-authors are named. Each contributor links to their Wikipedia article.

# Founders of quantum mechanics

- [Max Planck](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Max_Planck) (1858-1947): "A new
  scientific truth does not triumph by convincing its opponents and making them
  see the light, but rather because its opponents eventually die, and a new
  generation grows up that is familiar with it." Source: _Scientific
  Autobiography and Other Papers_, trans. F. Gaynor (1949), p. 33.
- [Albert Einstein](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein) (1879-1955):
  "Quantum mechanics is very impressive. But an inner voice tells me that it is
  not yet the real thing. ... In any case I am convinced that He does not throw
  dice" (der Alte wurfelt nicht). Source: letter to Max Born, 4 December 1926,
  in _The Born-Einstein Letters_ (1971).
- [Niels Bohr](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niels_Bohr) (1885-1962): "The very
  nature of the quantum theory thus forces us to regard the space-time
  coordination and the claim of causality ... as complementary but exclusive
  features of the description." Source: "The Quantum Postulate and the Recent
  Development of Atomic Theory," _Nature_ 121 (1928), p. 580.
- [Louis de Broglie](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Louis_de_Broglie)
  (1892-1987): "the existence of corpuscles accompanied by waves has to be
  assumed in all cases." Source: "The wave nature of the electron," Nobel
  Lecture, 1929.
- [Werner Heisenberg](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Werner_Heisenberg)
  (1901-1976): "What we observe is not nature itself but nature exposed to our
  method of questioning." Source: _Physics and Philosophy: The Revolution in
  Modern Science_ (1958), ch. 3, p. 78.
- [Erwin Schrodinger](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erwin_Schr%C3%B6dinger)
  (1887-1961): "I would not call \[entanglement\] one but rather _the_
  characteristic trait of quantum mechanics, the one that enforces its entire
  departure from classical lines of thought." Source: "Discussion of Probability
  Relations between Separated Systems," _Proc. Camb. Phil. Soc._ 31 (1935),
  p. 555.
- [Max Born](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Max_Born) (1882-1970): "The
  determinism of classical physics turns out to be an illusion, created by
  overrating mathematico-logical concepts. It is an idol, not an ideal in
  scientific research." Source: "The statistical interpretation of quantum
  mechanics," Nobel Lecture, 1954.
- [Paul Dirac](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Dirac) (1902-1984): "God is a
  mathematician of a very high order, and He used very advanced mathematics in
  constructing the universe." Source: "The Evolution of the Physicist's Picture
  of Nature," _Scientific American_ 208(5) (1963).
- [Wolfgang Pauli](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolfgang_Pauli) (1900-1958): "I
  had always the feeling, and I still have it today, that this is a deficiency"
  (on being unable to derive the exclusion principle from more general
  assumptions). Source: "Exclusion Principle and Quantum Mechanics," Nobel
  Lecture, 1946.

# The mathematical foundations

- [David Hilbert](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Hilbert) (1862-1943): "We
  must know. We will know" (Wir mussen wissen. Wir werden wissen). Source:
  closing lines of "Naturerkennen und Logik," address at Konigsberg, 8 September
  1930.
- [John von Neumann](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_von_Neumann)
  (1903-1957): "The most vitally characteristic fact about mathematics is, in my
  opinion, its quite peculiar relationship to the natural sciences." Source:
  "The Mathematician," in _The Works of the Mind_, ed. R. B. Heywood (1947).
- [Hermann Weyl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Weyl) (1885-1955):
  "Symmetry, as wide or as narrow as you may define its meaning, is one idea by
  which man through the ages has tried to comprehend and create order, beauty,
  and perfection." Source: _Symmetry_ (1952), p. 5.
- [Eugene Wigner](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugene_Wigner) (1902-1995): "The
  miracle of the appropriateness of the language of mathematics for the
  formulation of the laws of physics is a wonderful gift which we neither
  understand nor deserve." Source: "The Unreasonable Effectiveness of
  Mathematics in the Natural Sciences," _Comm. Pure Appl. Math._ 13 (1960).
- [Emmy Noether](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emmy_Noether) (1882-1935): "My
  methods are really methods of working and thinking; this is why they have
  crept in everywhere anonymously." Source: letter to Helmut Hasse, 12 November
  1931 (translated; in A. Dick, _Emmy Noether 1882-1935_, 1970).

# Entanglement, measurement, and nonlocality

- [Einstein, Podolsky, and Rosen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Einstein%E2%80%93Podolsky%E2%80%93Rosen_paradox)
  (1935): "If, without in any way disturbing a system, we can predict with
  certainty ... the value of a physical quantity, then there exists an element
  of reality corresponding to this physical quantity." Source: "Can
  Quantum-Mechanical Description of Physical Reality Be Considered Complete?,"
  _Phys. Rev._ 47 (1935), p. 777.
- [John Stewart Bell](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Stewart_Bell)
  (1928-1990): "Theoretical physicists live in a classical world, looking out
  into a quantum-mechanical world." Source: _Speakable and Unspeakable in
  Quantum Mechanics_ (1987), from "Introduction to the hidden-variable question"
  (1971).
- [David Bohm](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Bohm) (1917-1992): "The new
  form of insight can perhaps best be called Undivided Wholeness in Flowing
  Movement." Source: _Wholeness and the Implicate Order_ (1980), p. 11.
- [Hugh Everett III](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_Everett_III)
  (1930-1982): "all elements of a superposition (all 'branches') are 'actual',
  none any more 'real' than the rest." Source: "'Relative State' Formulation of
  Quantum Mechanics," _Rev. Mod. Phys._ 29 (1957), note added in proof.
- [Wojciech Zurek](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wojciech_H._Zurek) (1951-): "Decoherence
  is caused by the interaction in which the environment monitors certain
  observables of the system." Source: "Decoherence, einselection, and the
  quantum origins of the classical," _Rev. Mod. Phys._ 75 (2003), p. 715.
- [John Archibald Wheeler](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Archibald_Wheeler)
  (1911-2008): "It from bit. ... every _it_ ... derives its function, its
  meaning, its very existence ... from ... apparatus-elicited answers to yes-or-
  no questions, binary choices, bits." Source: "Information, Physics, Quantum:
  The Search for Links," in _Complexity, Entropy, and the Physics of
  Information_ (1990).
- [Richard Feynman](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Feynman) (1918-1988):
  "I think I can safely say that nobody understands quantum mechanics." Source:
  _The Character of Physical Law_ (1965), ch. 6.

# Geometry and the algebraic view

- [Yakir Aharonov](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yakir_Aharonov) (1932-), with
  David Bohm: "there exist effects of potentials on charged particles, even in
  the region where all the fields ... vanish." Source: Y. Aharonov and D. Bohm,
  "Significance of Electromagnetic Potentials in the Quantum Theory," _Phys.
  Rev._ 115 (1959), p. 485.
- [Michael Berry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Berry_%28physicist%29)
  (1941-): "What we call 'discovery' sometimes looks, in retrospect, more like
  emergence into the air from subterranean intellectual currents." Source:
  "Anticipations of the Geometric Phase," _Physics Today_ 43(12) (1990), p. 34.
- [Alain Connes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alain_Connes) (1947-), on the
  Platonist view behind noncommutative geometry: "There exists, independently of
  the human mind, a raw and immutable mathematical reality." Source: J.-P.
  Changeux and A. Connes, _Conversations on Mind, Matter and Mathematics_ (1995),
  spoken by Connes.

# Quantum information and the categorical turn

- [Richard Feynman](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Feynman) (1918-1988),
  on quantum computation: "Nature isn't classical, dammit, and if you want to
  make a simulation of nature, you'd better make it quantum mechanical." Source:
  "Simulating Physics with Computers," _Int. J. Theor. Phys._ 21 (1982), p. 486.
- [David Deutsch](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Deutsch) (1953-): "When
  Shor's algorithm has factorized a number, using 10^500 or so times the
  computational resources that can be seen to be present, where was the number
  factorized?" Source: _The Fabric of Reality_ (1997), ch. 9.
- [Peter Shor](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Shor) (1959-): "A digital
  computer is generally believed to be an efficient universal computing device
  ... This may not be true when quantum mechanics is taken into consideration."
  Source: "Polynomial-Time Algorithms for Prime Factorization and Discrete
  Logarithms on a Quantum Computer," _SIAM J. Comput._ 26 (1997).
- [Charles Bennett](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_H._Bennett_%28physicist%29)
  (1943-), with Brassard, Crepeau, Jozsa, Peres, and Wootters: "An unknown
  quantum state can be disassembled into, then later reconstructed from, purely
  classical information and purely nonclassical Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen (EPR)
  correlations." Source: "Teleporting an Unknown Quantum State via Dual Classical
  and Einstein-Podolsky-Rosen Channels," _Phys. Rev. Lett._ 70 (1993), p. 1895.
- [Samson Abramsky](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samson_Abramsky) (1953-) and
  [Bob Coecke](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Coecke) (1968-): "One of our
  main concerns is to replace ad hoc calculations with bras and kets,
  normalizing constants, unitary matrices etc. by conceptual definitions and
  proofs." Source: "A Categorical Semantics of Quantum Protocols," _Proc. 19th
  IEEE LICS_ (2004).
- [John C. Baez](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_C._Baez) (1961-), with Mike
  Stay: "By now there is an extensive network of interlocking analogies between
  physics, topology, logic and computer science." Source: "Physics, Topology,
  Logic and Computation: A Rosetta Stone" (2011), arXiv:0903.0340.

# Contributors without an included quotation

These figures shaped the field's mathematics but have no short, primary-sourced
line we could verify to print here (their legacy is in monographs and theorems,
not aphorisms). They are listed for completeness.

- [Israel Gelfand](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Israel_Gelfand) (1913-2009) and
  [Mark Naimark](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Naimark) (1909-1978):
  C\*-algebras and the GNS construction, the charter of the operator-algebraic
  view.
- [George Mackey](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Mackey) (1916-2006): the
  imprimitivity theorem and systems of representations.
- [Rudolf Haag](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudolf_Haag) (1922-2016):
  algebraic quantum field theory.
- [Bertram Kostant](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bertram_Kostant) (1928-2017),
  [Jean-Marie Souriau](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Marie_Souriau)
  (1922-2012), and
  [Alexandre Kirillov](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandre_Kirillov)
  (1936-): geometric quantization and the orbit method.
- [Barry Simon](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barry_Simon) (1946-): mathematical
  physics, and the geometric phase as holonomy.

# A note on authenticity

Several of the most famous "quantum quotes" are not printed above because they
do not survive a check against primary sources. Naming them is part of the same
discipline the rest of the book follows.

- Niels Bohr, "Anyone who is not shocked by quantum theory has not understood
  it": not found in Bohr's writings; it traces to a recollection in Heisenberg's
  _Physics and Beyond_ (1971) and is absent from Bohr's collected works.
- Wolfgang Pauli, "not even wrong" and "I mind your publishing faster than you
  think": both are anecdotal (a Peierls recollection and a 1977 quotation
  compilation), not in Pauli's own publications.
- John von Neumann, "In mathematics you don't understand things, you just get
  used to them": a second-hand recollection reported via G. Zukav's _The Dancing
  Wu Li Masters_ (1979), not a primary source.
- Hermann Weyl, "when I had to choose ... I usually chose the beautiful": a
  remark reported by Freeman Dyson in a _Nature_ obituary (1956), not Weyl's own
  written words.
- Albert Einstein, "God does not play dice with the universe": the 1926 letter
  to Born says only that "He does not throw dice"; the "with the universe" tag is
  a later embellishment.
- Richard Feynman, "Shut up and calculate!": actually
  [N. David Mermin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N._David_Mermin), _Physics
  Today_ 42(4) (1989); Mermin later documented the misattribution to Feynman in
  _Physics Today_ 57(5) (2004).
- Emmy Noether, "the most significant creative mathematical genius thus far
  produced since the higher education of women began": this praise is _by_
  Einstein (a letter to _The New York Times_, 1935) _about_ Noether, not a
  quotation of her.

